article.description:
The Chicago Bulls accomplished this much Monday
night: they double-teamed Tracy McGrady and kept him below his average.
article.headline: McGrady shows off all his talents with near triple double
article.linkText: Bulls find out McGrady can do more than just score
article.story:
CHICAGO (AP) -- The Chicago Bulls accomplished this much Monday night: they double-teamed Tracy McGrady and kept him below his league-leading scoring average.
McGrady

What they couldn't do was prevent the Orlando star from controlling the game with his other talents and leading the Magic to another victory. ''I've received double-teams for a while now and I know how to handle that,'' McGrady said after scoring 26 points, tying a career high with 13 assists and getting nine rebounds as the Magic beat the Bulls 104-89 for their sixth victory in seven games. ''I know where my guys are on the weakside and if they want to double, fine. It's not about me going out and trying to score 30 or 40 points. I'm just trying to get the win. I'm sacrificing when they double.'' McGrady shot just 6-for-19 but had eight of his points in the final 4:45 to fight off a final Bulls rally. ''He did a good job with his assists and knew where to find his guys,'' Chicago's Donyell Marshall said. ''He's 6-foot-8 and sees over guys and they've got good spot-up shooters,'' Chicago coach Bill Cartwright said. Benefiting from the focus on McGrady, Orlando's Pat Garrity scored 21 points, making five 3-pointers. Gordon Giricek scored 18, Darrell Armstrong 14 and Drew Gooden 13 for the Magic. Jalen Rose led the Bulls with 24 points and Marshall had 15. After the game, frustrated Chicago rookie Jay Williams, who went scoreless in 22 minutes, suggested that it was time the 21-41 Bulls made some changes. ''You lose so many games, it's definitely frustrating. It makes you second guess yourself and everything else going on here,'' said Williams, the No. 2 choice in the draft last year. ''Maybe it's time to do things differently.'' Meanwhile, Orlando rookies Gooden and Giricek provided a spark. Gooden had six points and Giricek five in a 20-6 run to start the third quarter as the Magic pulled out to a 17-point lead. McGrady, who was averaging 31.2 points entering the game, had scorched the Bulls for 52 points in just 33 minutes when the teams met 10 days ago, going 15-for-32 from the field. Every time McGrady drove to the basket this time, the Bulls collapsed on him. So several times he kicked the ball back out and ended the first half with eight assists and 11 points on 3-for-7 shooting. Chicago staged a mini-rally in the fourth quarter with a 12-4 run to close to nine. But McGrady went baseline for a dunk, hit a jumper and made four free throws before Garrity hit a 3-pointer as the Magic regained control. ''He's amazing,'' Orlando coach Doc Rivers said of McGrady. ''He didn't have a good shooting night and he was still one rebound away from a triple-double. I thought down the stretch he took the game over.'' Game notes
Needing one rebound for a triple-double, McGrady tried to crash the boards several times in the final two minutes before he was pulled from the game in the closing seconds. ... Orlando is 5-1 since trading for Giricek and Gooden on Feb. 19. ... Orlando has won 16 of its past 18 meetings with the Bulls. ... Rose, who played in 83 games last season -- getting an extra game after being traded from the Pacers to the Bulls -- is on course to start all 82 for the Bulls. He suffered a chipped tooth in the defeat Saturday against the Wizards when he was fouled hard by Michael Jordan, but was ready to go Monday. ''It's important for me to bring it every night,'' he said. ... Gooden had 10 rebounds and Marshall had 11 for the Bulls. Chicago had 21 turnovers.
